# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: harry-swacina
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:harry-swacina/1901-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1901 throughout the world.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1907 throughout the world.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The **1907 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1907.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 6, with the Chicago Cubs and Detroit Tigers as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the fourth modern World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 5 on October 12.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The Cubs defeated the Tigers, four games to none (with one tie), capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Chicago White Sox from the 1906 season.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Beaneaters renamed as the Boston Doves.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The 1907 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 11 with all but the Brooklyn Superbas and Boston Doves playing.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 6.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 12.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] 30 tie games (18 in AL, 12 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 12 with the Chicago Cubs defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1907 World Series in five games (one of which being a tie).
[src:harry-swacina/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1908 throughout the world.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The **1908 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1908.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 8, with the Chicago Cubs and Detroit Tigers as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-major-league-baseball-season] In a rematch of the prior year's postseason, the postseason began with Game 1 of the fifth modern World Series on October 10 and ended with Game 5 on October 14.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), The Cubs defeated the Tigers, four games to one, capturing their second championship in franchise history, and the first team to win back-to-back World Series.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Americans renamed as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The 1908 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 with all but the Pittsburgh Pirates and St.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 8.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 10 and October 14.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games (10 in AL, 6 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 10 and ended on October 14 with the Chicago Cubs defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1908 World Series in five games.
[src:harry-swacina/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics would play their final game at Columbia Park with a doubleheader on October 3 against the Boston Red Sox, moving into Shibe Park for the start of the 1909 season.
[src:harry-swacina/1911-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1911 throughout the world.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The **1914 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1914, with the first game of the inaugural major league season of the Federal League (having previously existed as a minor league the year before).
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The league declared itself as a "third major league", with its own eight teams, in competition with the established National and American Leagues.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National League regular season ended on October 6 with the Boston Braves as champions, and the American League regular season concluded the next day with the Philadelphia Athletics as champions.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League season ended on October 10, and saw the Indianapolis Hoosiers winning the Federal League pennant.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the National and American Leagues began with Game 1 of the 11th World Series on October 9 and ended with Game 4 on October 13.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Braves swept the Athletics in four games, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Both the National and American Leagues rejected offers by the Federal League for a postseason matchup.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Philadelphia Athletics from the 1913 season.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each of the established National and American Leagues.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers renamed as the Brooklyn Robins.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The major-league status of the Federal League was confirmed by the Special Baseball Records Committee (as convened by then-Commissioner of Baseball William Eckert) in 1969.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The 1914 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League, National League, and Federal League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format first put in place for the 1904 season, and which lasted until the 140-game schedule of 1919.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Most teams played more than 154 games, due to tie games (called on account of darkness or weather) that had to be replayed; tie games are excluded from team standings, but the statistics of individual players are included in their season totals.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had its Opening Day on April 13, with a game between Buffalo and Baltimore.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day for the American and National Leagues was on April 14, and featured all 16 teams of those leagues, only the third time those two leagues started their season on the same day (the 1912 season had been the second).
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National League had its final day of the regular season on October 6, while the American League's final day of the regular season was October 7.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series between AL and NL champions took place between October 9 and October 13.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had the final day of its regular season on October 10.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] 43 tie games (18 in AL, 10 in NL, 15 in FL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 9 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Braves sweeping the Philadelphia Athletics in the 1914 World Series in four games.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National and American Leagues refused a postseason against the Federal League.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Across two leagues, Dave Davenport tied as a leader in saves at 6 (2 with the Cincinnati Reds of the NL and 4 with the St.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Note: Attendance data for Federal League teams is unavailable.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] They previously played their on August 1 and August 8.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] In all, 29 of their 79 home games were played at Fenway Park.
[src:harry-swacina/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The team would only play at Fenway through July of the following season.
[src:harry-swacina/harry-swacina] Swacina began his professional career in 1901 with the minor league Memphis Egyptians of the Southern Association.
[src:harry-swacina/harry-swacina] He was playing for the Peoria Distillers of the Three-I League in 1907 when he was picked up by the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:harry-swacina/harry-swacina] He was inserted as the regular first baseman in mid-September, replacing the departed Jim Nealon, and batted .200 in 26 games.
[src:harry-swacina/harry-swacina] Swacina returned to the Pirates in 1908, where he split time at first base with Alan Storke and Jim Kane.
[src:harry-swacina/harry-swacina] In August, his contract was sold to the Louisville Colonels, and he spent the next several years back in the minor leagues, including a stint as player-manager with the Mobile Sea Gulls in 1911.
[src:harry-swacina/harry-swacina] In 1914, the creation of the Federal League offered Swacina the opportunity to return to the majors.
[src:harry-swacina/harry-swacina] That season, he served as the regular first baseman for the Baltimore Terrapins.
[src:harry-swacina/harry-swacina] In 1915, he split the first base duties for the Terrapins with Joe Agler.
[src:harry-swacina/harry-swacina] When the Federal League folded after the season, Swacina again returned to the minor leagues.
[src:harry-swacina/harry-swacina] He continued to play professionally until 1923, a season which he split between the Jackson Senators of the Cotton States League and the Greenville Spinners of the South Atlantic League.
